,"links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6843"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14160"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41375"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4995"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44198"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55829"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent due to concerns about loose stools for the past three months. He has three to four loose stools per day, often containing visible undigested food particles. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. His parent reports that he is otherwise well, active, and growing normally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His weight and height are at the 50th percentile for his age. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. There are no signs of dehydration or malnutrition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Order stool culture and sensitivity","Perform abdominal ultrasound","Reassure parent and provide dietary advice","Refer to paediatric gastroenterologist","Order serum electrolytes and renal function tests"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a classic picture of toddler\u0027s diarrhoea, a common and benign condition in children aged 1-5 years. The key features are chronic loose stools containing undigested food particles in an otherwise healthy, growing child. Given these characteristics and the absence of red flag symptoms, the most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassure the parent and provide dietary advice\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrdering stool culture and sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary in this case. Toddler\u0027s diarrhoea is a clinical diagnosis based on the typical history and normal growth. In the absence of symptoms suggesting infection (such as fever, blood in stools, or recent travel), stool cultures are not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming an abdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate for this presentation. There are no signs or symptoms suggesting abdominal pathology that would warrant imaging studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to a paediatric gastroenterologist\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary for uncomplicated toddler\u0027s diarrhoea. This condition can be managed effectively in primary care with reassurance and dietary modifications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrdering serum electrolytes and renal function tests\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. The child shows no signs of dehydration or systemic illness that would necessitate these investigations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of toddler\u0027s diarrhoea primarily involves reassurance that this is a benign, self-limiting condition. Dietary advice may include reducing excess fluid intake (especially fruit juices), increasing fat intake, and reducing sorbitol-containing foods. It\u0027s important to emphasize that the child is growing well and that this condition typically resolves spontaneously by school age. If symptoms worsen or new concerning symptoms develop, further evaluation may be warranted at that time.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Toddler\u0027s diarrhoea is a common, benign condition that does not require stool samples or other investigations for diagnosis.","Toddler\u0027s diarrhoea is typically characterized by frequent, loose stools with undigested food particles in an otherwise healthy, growing child.","Reassurance and dietary modifications are the mainstay of management for toddler\u0027s diarrhoea."],"references":["Denk L. Diarrhea, Toddler\u0027s. Pediatric Clinical Advisor. 2007:171\u20132. doi: 10.1016/B978-032303506-4.10095-1. Epub 2009 May 22. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7151931/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41375"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14160"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41375"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T11:44:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T11:44:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6843"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55829"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}